  "prompt": "When should I stop using the teeth gap bands on my teeth?",
  "response": "When considering the use of teeth gap bands, it is crucial to prioritize safety and professional guidance. Here\u2019s a concise, organized answer:\n\n### **When to Stop Using Teeth Gap Bands:**\n1. **Immediately**: \n   - **Dentists strongly advise against using gap bands** due to risks like tooth loss, root damage, gum recession, infection, and misalignment. These risks outweigh any potential benefits.\n   - **DIY orthodontics is unsafe**; bands can slip below the gumline, causing severe harm even before visible issues arise.\n\n2. **If You Notice Any of These Signs** (stop immediately and see a dentist):\n   - Pain, swelling, or bleeding gums.\n   - Loose teeth or changes in bite alignment.\n   - Bands migrating toward the roots or gums.\n   - The gap appears closed (improper movement may still cause hidden damage).\n\n3. **Permanent Solution**:\n   - **Consult an orthodontist** for safe, effective treatments (e.g., braces, clear aligners, or retainers). Professional supervision ensures proper tooth movement and long-term oral health.\n\n### **Key Takeaway:**\nDiscontinue gap bands **now** and seek professional care. Orthodontic treatment requires precise, monitored techniques to avoid irreversible harm. Your dental health is worth the investment in safe, expert solutions.",
